Pyrrho and Arcesilas had maintained that all we can do is to act upon phenomena without attempting to determine their truth or falsehood. Carneades, equally holding that certainty is a chimera, contended that reason could lead up to sundry approximations to certainty, which were the proper bases for action.

The question whether action was possible without certainty was much talked oi by the disputants‚ but the debate on this topic amounted in essence to nothing but assertion and denial.
